<figureCitation box="[299,385,2003,2029]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="13.[214,225,1567,1585]" captionTargetBox="[134,1453,233,1515]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[134,1457,214,1515]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIG. 8. — Lecteria (Lecteria) wayana n. sp. male, holotype: A, wing; B, head; C, detail of the first antennal flagellomeres. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726020" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726020/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="508">Figs 8B</figureCitation>
; 
<figureCitation box="[397,432,2003,2029]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[307,318,1689,1707]" captionTargetBox="[135,1456,215,1645]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[134,1457,215,1645]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 9. — Thorax of Lecteria (Lecteria) wayana n. sp. male, holotype: A, lateral view; B, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726022" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726022/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="508">9A</figureCitation>
), 4 palpomeres, ovoid, with the fourth longer than the third. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[1231,1314,1652,1678]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="13.[214,225,1567,1585]" captionTargetBox="[134,1453,233,1515]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[134,1457,214,1515]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIG. 8. — Lecteria (Lecteria) wayana n. sp. male, holotype: A, wing; B, head; C, detail of the first antennal flagellomeres. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726020" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726020/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="508">Fig. 8C</figureCitation>
) pale brown, 16-segmented. Scape and pedicel pale brown, latter with second half brown. Flagellum with 14 flagellomeres, pale yellowish to white, progressively paler (whiter) towards the apex. Flagellomeres 1 to 5 oval, decreasing in length towards antennal apex, longer and slightly wider than the remaining flagellomeres. As in 
<taxonomicName authority="Mederos &amp; Pollet, 2019" authorityName="Mederos &amp; Pollet" authorityYear="2019" box="[1022,1239,1843,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Limoniidae" genus="Lecteria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="508" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitarakanea" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1022,1239,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="508">Lecteria mitarakanea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1244,1303,1844,1870]" pageId="13" pageNumber="508" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, basal 5 flagellomeres covered with short and thin microsetae and with one single verticil, except for the first segment of right antennal segment with two, the outermost verticil being the longest. Last 9 segments with 4 or 5 verticils, not covered with thin microsetae, and last flagellomere with 8 verticils.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726022" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3726022" box="[307,1283,1689,1707]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726022/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="509" startId="14.[307,318,1689,1707]" targetBox="[135,1456,215,1645]" targetPageId="14">
<paragraph blockId="14.[307,1283,1689,1707]" box="[307,1283,1689,1707]" pageId="14" pageNumber="509">
FIG. 9. — Thorax of 
<taxonomicName authority="Mederos &amp; Pollet, 2019" authorityName="Mederos &amp; Pollet" authorityYear="2019" box="[471,687,1689,1707]" class="Insecta" family="Limoniidae" genus="Lecteria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="509" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wayana" status="n. sp." subGenus="Lecteria">
<emphasis box="[471,537,1689,1707]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="509">Lecteria</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[547,613,1689,1707]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="509">Lecteria</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[624,687,1689,1707]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="509">wayana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[691,739,1689,1707]" pageId="14" pageNumber="509" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
male, holotype: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[876,889,1689,1707]" pageId="14" pageNumber="509">A</emphasis>
, lateral view; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1003,1016,1689,1707]" pageId="14" pageNumber="509">B</emphasis>
, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="14.[132,776,1779,2030]" lastBlockId="15.[132,775,855,945]" lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="510" pageId="14" pageNumber="509">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,217,1779,1805]" pageId="14" pageNumber="509">Thorax.</emphasis>
Brown to dark brown, with some pale brown areas. Pronotum brown to dark brown. Mesoscutum dark brown, with two very pale brown longitudinal stripes, parallel, from prescutum to almost transverse suture, both stripes separated by a thin grayish brown strip (
<figureCitation box="[444,525,1907,1933]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[307,318,1689,1707]" captionTargetBox="[135,1456,215,1645]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[134,1457,215,1645]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 9. — Thorax of Lecteria (Lecteria) wayana n. sp. male, holotype: A, lateral view; B, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726022" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726022/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="509">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
). Another two very pale brown lateral stripes, one at each side, of above mentioned stripes, reaching beyond the transverse suture. Scutellum brown. Mediotergite brown on basal half, yellowish pale to white in apical half. Anepisternum and katepisternum pale brown with a small brown area at anterior edge. Anepimeron with pale brown anterior half, and brown posterior half. Laterotergite with brown anterior half, and pale brown posterior half. This color pattern featuring a discrete effect of two very pale brown transverse stripes in the middle of a brown area: the first (anterior) stripe running from the upper part of anepisternum to the middle coxa, the second (posterior) stripe from the upper part of anepimeron to the posterior coxa (
<figureCitation box="[140,226,887,913]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="14.[307,318,1689,1707]" captionTargetBox="[135,1456,215,1645]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[134,1457,215,1645]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIG. 9. — Thorax of Lecteria (Lecteria) wayana n. sp. male, holotype: A, lateral view; B, dorsal view. Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726022" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726022/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Fig. 9A</figureCitation>
). Halter with stem very pale brown, almost white, and knob pale brown.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726024" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3726024" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726024/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" startId="15.[136,147,752,770]" targetBox="[143,1410,230,700]" targetPageId="15">
<paragraph blockId="15.[136,1417,752,792]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">
FIG. 10. — 
<taxonomicName authority="Mederos &amp; Pollet, 2019" authorityName="Mederos &amp; Pollet" authorityYear="2019" box="[226,442,752,770]" class="Insecta" family="Limoniidae" genus="Lecteria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wayana" status="n. sp." subGenus="Lecteria">
<emphasis box="[226,292,752,770]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Lecteria</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[303,369,752,770]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Lecteria</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[379,442,752,770]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">wayana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[447,495,752,770]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
male, holotype: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[632,645,752,770]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">A</emphasis>
, terminalia, dorsal view; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[851,864,752,770]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">B</emphasis>
, terminalia, ventral view; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1075,1089,752,770]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">C</emphasis>
, aedeagal complex (dorsal view). Scale bars: 0.5 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="15.[132,775,982,1104]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,201,982,1008]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Wing.</emphasis>
Almost hyaline, with a very subtle brownish pale tinge, without spots or any color pattern except the light brownish stigmal area (
<figureCitation box="[274,359,1046,1072]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="13.[214,225,1567,1585]" captionTargetBox="[134,1453,233,1515]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[134,1457,214,1515]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIG. 8. — Lecteria (Lecteria) wayana n. sp. male, holotype: A, wing; B, head; C, detail of the first antennal flagellomeres. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726020" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726020/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Fig. 8A</figureCitation>
). Veins light brownish, distinct against the hyaline background color of the wing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[132,776,1141,1742]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,190,1141,1167]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Legs.</emphasis>
Coxae pale brown, almost white in dorsal half. All legs with the same color pattern. Femora pale brown in slightly more than basal half, followed by a brown band, another pale brown band, slightly shorter than more basal brown band, and finally another dark brown band at apex, approximately as long as the more basal pale brown band. Scarce, short brown setae in the basal half of femur, until the beginning of the most basal brown band, latter with many brown setae. The pale brown band, in between the two brown bands, with white setae. Tibiae with tibial spurs lacking; with basal short pale brown band, followed by a whitish equal-sized band. Next, the entire central extension pale brown, interrupted by another whitish band, longer than more basal whitish band, and short pale brown band at apex. Tarsi with tarsomere I almost completely pale brown, whitish at apex. Tarsomeres II to IV whitish, all subtle pale brown at extreme apex. Tarsomere V pale brown. All legs with many long setae in the colored bands, concolorous with the respective bands. Tarsal claws dark brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[132,776,1779,1934]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,248,1779,1805]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Abdomen.</emphasis>
All tergites brown to dark brown, with some paler areas, without any distinct pattern. Sternites brown with some pale brown areas. Tergites and sternites progressively darker towards the apex of the abdomen. Sides of the abdomen with a dark brown stripe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[132,775,1971,2030]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[132,261,1971,1997]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Terminalia.</emphasis>
Tergite 9 dark brown, approximately twice as wide as long (
<figureCitation box="[285,386,2003,2029]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[136,147,752,770]" captionTargetBox="[143,1410,230,700]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[132,1455,216,719]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIG. 10. — Lecteria (Lecteria) wayana n. sp. male, holotype: A, terminalia, dorsal view; B, terminalia, ventral view; C, aedeagal complex (dorsal view). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726024" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726024/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Fig. 10A</figureCitation>
). Gonocoxite cone-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[691,769,2003,2029]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="5.[132,143,1940,1958]" captionTargetBox="[204,1390,221,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[182,1404,204,1896]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIG. 1. — Terminalia of Neotropical species of Lecteria (Lecteria) Osten Sacken, 1888: A, L. acanthosoma Alexander, 1969; B, L. acanthostyla Alexander, 1969; C, L. bicornuta Alexander, 1969; D, L. cetrata Alexander, 1969; E, L. fuscitarsis Alexander, 1969; F, L. retrorsa Alexander, 1969; G, L. simplex Alexander, 1969; H, L. upsilon Alexander, 1969; I, L. calopus (Walker, 1856); J, L. wayana n. sp.; K, L. mitarakanea n. sp.; L, L. teko n. sp. A-H, modified by Alexander (1969); I, modified by Ribeiro &amp; Blagoderov (2009)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726006" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726006/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Figs 1J</figureCitation>
;
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[813,1456,855,1040]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">
<figureCitation box="[813,896,855,882]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[136,147,752,770]" captionTargetBox="[143,1410,230,700]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[132,1455,216,719]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIG. 10. — Lecteria (Lecteria) wayana n. sp. male, holotype: A, terminalia, dorsal view; B, terminalia, ventral view; C, aedeagal complex (dorsal view). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726024" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726024/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">10A, B</figureCitation>
), almost cylindrical, about twice as long as wide. Outer gonostylus slightly longer than inner gonostylus. Outer gonostylus at apex divided in two small spike-shaped processes. Aedeagal complex (
<figureCitation box="[1132,1232,951,977]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="15.[136,147,752,770]" captionTargetBox="[143,1410,230,700]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[132,1455,216,719]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIG. 10. — Lecteria (Lecteria) wayana n. sp. male, holotype: A, terminalia, dorsal view; B, terminalia, ventral view; C, aedeagal complex (dorsal view). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3726024" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3726024/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
): aedeagus short and straigh, not surpassing the interbase; interbase with a deep cleft in the central posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[813,930,1078,1136]" box="[813,886,1078,1104]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">
<emphasis box="[813,886,1078,1104]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Female</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[813,930,1078,1136]" box="[813,930,1110,1136]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="510" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[813,1456,1173,1710]" box="[813,913,1173,1199]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[813,1456,1173,1710]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">
According to the key by 
<bibRefCitation author="ALEXANDER C. P." box="[1081,1271,1206,1232]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" pagination="321 - 340" refId="ref8710" refString="ALEXANDER C. P. 1969. - A revision of the Tropical American species of the genus Lecteria Osten-Sacken (Tipulidae, Diptera). Studia Entomologica 12: 321 - 340." type="journal article" year="1969">Alexander (1969)</bibRefCitation>
<taxonomicName authority="Mederos &amp; Pollet, 2019" authorityName="Mederos &amp; Pollet" authorityYear="2019" box="[1278,1388,1206,1231]" class="Insecta" family="Limoniidae" genus="Lecteria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wayana" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1278,1388,1206,1231]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">L. wayana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1396,1456,1206,1232]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
would fit the species group with “a darkened pattern of wing restricted”, which includes 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1805" box="[1105,1236,1269,1295]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Tipula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armillaris">
<emphasis box="[1105,1236,1269,1295]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">L. armillaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alexander" authorityYear="1913" box="[1290,1448,1270,1295]" class="Insecta" family="Limoniidae" genus="Lecteria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mattogrossae">
<emphasis box="[1290,1448,1270,1295]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">L. mattogrossae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These two species, described from specimens with broken abdomen and therefore of unknown sex (
<bibRefCitation author="ALEXANDER C. P." box="[1267,1439,1333,1359]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" pagination="321 - 340" refId="ref8710" refString="ALEXANDER C. P. 1969. - A revision of the Tropical American species of the genus Lecteria Osten-Sacken (Tipulidae, Diptera). Studia Entomologica 12: 321 - 340." type="journal article" year="1969">Alexander 1969</bibRefCitation>
), however, show many differences with respect to 
<taxonomicName authority="Mederos &amp; Pollet, 2019" authorityName="Mederos &amp; Pollet" authorityYear="2019" box="[1344,1455,1366,1391]" class="Insecta" family="Limoniidae" genus="Lecteria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wayana" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1344,1455,1366,1391]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">L. wayana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[813,871,1398,1424]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
<taxonomicName authority="Mederos &amp; Pollet, 2019" authorityName="Mederos &amp; Pollet" authorityYear="2019" box="[878,1047,1398,1423]" class="Insecta" family="Limoniidae" genus="Lecteria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wayana" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[878,1047,1398,1423]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">Lecteria wayana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1054,1112,1398,1424]" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
features brown pleura with two very pale brown, almost white, transverse stripes in the middle and a dark brown mesoscutum with two long pale brown longitudinal stripes in the center, parallel, and accompanied by another two, also pale brown, lateral stripes. On the contrary, in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1805" box="[907,1038,1556,1582]" class="Insecta" family="Bibionidae" genus="Tipula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armillaris">
<emphasis box="[907,1038,1556,1582]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">L. armillaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the mesonotum is reddish brown and pleura somewhat pruinose, with a row of brown spots, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alexander" authorityYear="1913" box="[813,969,1621,1646]" class="Insecta" family="Limoniidae" genus="Lecteria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="510" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mattogrossae">
<emphasis box="[813,969,1621,1646]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="510">L. mattogrossae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows a brown mesonotum with three darker brown bands, and grayish yellow pleura with a dark brown longitudinal stripe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
